{
    "analysis": "We confirmed all four telemetry files are present and cover the suspected incident window (timestamps ~1647837000 → 1647838740; error_logs extend slightly further). Metric and trace volumes are large; error_logs concentrate on frontend pods (frontend-1, frontend-0). To follow the prescribed workflow, the next step is to identify which metric KPIs correspond to resource and performance indicators (CPU, memory, network, I/O, JVM, etc.) so we can compute global thresholds (P95/P05) per component-KPI and then search for anomalies within the incident window. We need an explicit list of available kpi_name values (and their counts) to decide which KPIs to include in threshold calculations. This has not been fully enumerated yet (we only have top-50 examples), so we must retrieve a compact, sorted list of kpi_name keys and flag those matching resource-related keyword patterns.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, return a compact table with: 1) total rows, ts_min, ts_max; 2) top 100 distinct kpi_name with their counts sorted descending; 3) for each returned kpi_name, include a boolean flag (or list) indicating whether it matches any of these case-insensitive substrings: 'cpu', 'memory', 'mem', 'heap', 'jvm', 'network', 'net', 'tx', 'rx', 'io', 'disk', 'read', 'write', 'latency', 'duration'. Also return top 20 distinct cmdb_id with counts from metric.csv. Limit output to these aggregates only (no raw time series)."}

{
    "analysis": "We have enumerated available KPIs and confirmed metric telemetry is concentrated on container network and I/O KPIs, with strong coverage across service pods (adservice, frontend, checkoutservice, productcatalogservice, cartservice, etc.). The next required step per the workflow is to compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) for each component-KPI time series using the full available series, then extract data within the incident window (March 21, 2022 12:30 → 13:00, UTC+8) and detect anomalies. Since many KPIs are resource-related (network, io, cpu, memory, jvm, disk, read/write, duration/latency), we should limit threshold calculation to component-KPI pairs whose kpi_name matches these token patterns. After thresholding, we will identify which component-KPIs show the most anomalies in the incident window so we can prioritize trace/log analysis. None of the root cause identity or time has been determined yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: 1) Identify all unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs whose kpi_name (case-insensitive) contains any of these tokens: 'cpu','memory','mem','heap','jvm','network','net','tx','rx','io','disk','read','write','latency','duration'. 2) For each pair, compute global P95 and P5 using the full available series (do NOT filter by time before computing thresholds). 3) Convert the incident window March 21, 2022 12:30 to 13:00 (UTC+8) to timestamps and filter the metric rows to that window. 4) For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair, compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_high = count(values >= P95), anomaly_count_low = count(values <= P5), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (earliest timestamp in window where value >=P95 or <=P5), P95, P5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. 5) Return a compact table of the top 20 pairs sorted by (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) descending; include the columns listed above. Limit output to these aggregated rows only (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric analysis found many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs with degenerate constant series (P95 == P5 and identical min/max), which makes simple threshold-based anomaly flags unreliable. Top metric anomalies are widespread but likely false positives due to constant-valued metrics. Meanwhile earlier file summaries showed error_logs concentrated in frontend pods (frontend-1, frontend-0). Because metric-derived candidates are ambiguous, we should now pivot to logs and traces to identify real failures: error_logs for explicit error messages and log.csv for aggregated log counters (e.g., log.error_count). Traces can help localize downstream faulty components once we identify candidate services/pods from logs. We have not yet determined the root cause component, exact occurrence time, or reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the incident window Mar 21, 2022 12:30 → 13:00 Asia/Shanghai (UTC+8), perform the following compact analyses (do NOT return raw time series):\n1) error_logs.csv: filter rows to the incident window. Return a table of top 20 cmdb_id by error count in-window with columns: cmdb_id, error_count_in_window, earliest_error_ts_in_window, latest_error_ts_in_window. For each of those top cmdb_id, also return up to top 5 distinct message prefixes (first 80 chars) with counts.\n2) log.csv: filter rows to the incident window. Aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) and return the top 20 groups by sum(value) (or by count if sums are identical). For each group include: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window, latest_ts_in_window.\n3) trace.csv: filter rows to the incident window. Return top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs by average value in-window with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, avg_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window. \nLimit each returned table to at most 20 rows and keep the outputs compact (aggregates only)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics, traces, and logs for the incident window. Metric-based anomaly detection produced many degenerate results (constant-valued series where P95 == P5), so metrics are currently inconclusive. Trace and log aggregates both point to the frontend layer as the primary area of activity and error volume during the window: frontend-1, frontend-0, and frontend-2 have the highest error_logs counts, the largest log.row_count sums, and the highest trace row_counts. To localize the root cause component, occurrence time, and reason we must inspect the actual error log contents and the precise earliest timestamps when frontend errors began. That will allow correlation with traces and logs to determine whether a frontend pod itself failed (e.g., process termination, out-of-memory, network errors) or it merely propagated downstream failures.\n\nTherefore we need the detailed, bounded error-log evidence for the frontend pods (and example full messages at the earliest error times) before proceeding to tie in traces or metric anomalies.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter error_logs.csv to the incident window (Mar 21, 2022 12:30 → 13:00 Asia/Shanghai UTC+8). Limit to cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2]. For each of these three cmdb_id return a compact row with: cmdb_id, total_error_count_in_window, earliest_error_timestamp_in_window, latest_error_timestamp_in_window, and the top 10 distinct message prefixes (first 200 characters) with counts. Additionally, for each cmdb_id, return up to 5 full error log messages that occurred at the earliest_error_timestamp_in_window (if there are fewer than 5 messages at that timestamp return all). Keep outputs compact and aggregated; do not return full raw file beyond these bounded results."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor searched traces for any adservice-related entries in the incident window and found none. Prior analyses showed the error log volume is dominated by a repeated message 'failed to retrieve ads' originating from frontend pods at the start of the window (earliest frontend timestamps 1647837000–1647837002). This strongly suggests frontend attempted to retrieve ads and failed repeatedly. However, because there are no adservice traces in the window, we cannot tell yet whether adservice itself failed or whether the issue is internal to frontend or in the network (e.g., frontend could not reach adservice but adservice produced no trace/logs). To decide whether adservice is the root cause, we must check whether adservice produced any error logs or abnormal log metrics in the same window. If adservice shows corresponding errors or resource anomalies, adservice is likely the root cause; if adservice shows no errors and normal logs/metrics, the root cause is likely a frontend-side or network issue.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Within the incident window Mar 21, 2022 12:30 → 13:00 (Asia/Shanghai UTC+8):\n1) From error_logs.csv filter rows where cmdb_id contains 'adservice' (case-insensitive). Return a compact table (max 20 rows) with: cmdb_id, error_count_in_window, earliest_error_ts_in_window, latest_error_ts_in_window, and top up to 10 distinct message prefixes (first 200 chars) with counts for that cmdb_id. If no rows match, explicitly return an empty result indication.\n2) From log.csv filter to the same window and cmdb_id containing 'adservice' (pods and services). Aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) and return up to top 20 groups sorted by sum(value) descending with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_points_in_window, sum_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, earliest_ts_in_window, latest_ts_in_window. \nKeep outputs strictly to these two aggregated tables (no raw time series)."
}

